You can tell a simple story about Elon Musk=E2=80=99s  pending acquisition =
of Twitter Inc. that goes like this. Musk offered Twitter $54.20 per share =
in cash. Twitter=E2=80=99s board of directors consulted some bankers, who t=
old them that the market price of Twitter=E2=80=99s stock was lower than $5=
4.20, and that it would likely stay lower in the near future, due to Twitte=
r not making all that much money. The board of directors had a fiduciary du=
ty to maximize the stock price for those shareholders. They looked for high=
er bids than $54.20, but none materialized. So they had no choice but to ta=
ke Musk=E2=80=99s $54.20.This simple story is the one that, for instance, T=
witter Chief Executive Officer Parag Agrawal told Twitter employees last we=
ek.[1]=C2=A0Casey Newton reports=C2=A0on a Twitter all-hands call Friday:Wh=
y did Agrawal vote in favor of the deal? He spoke in the bloodless language=
 of, well, a fiduciary.Agrawal:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CAs I=E2=80=99ve said, the boa=
rd decides based on two factors. We act in the interest of our shareholders=
 and look for value for them in the long term. Our job is to think about th=
e price, and consider any offer on the table. And we compare that against t=
he intrinsic value of the company based on the future-looking outlooks we h=
ave financially.=E2=80=9D=E2=80=9CWe get a lot of advice from several lawye=
rs and bankers in the process =E2=80=A6 And when we looked at all the infor=
mation and all of the data, every one of us concluded that based on our fid=
uciary responsibility =E2=80=A6 this offer at the price it ended up at was =
in the best long-term interest of our shareholders.=E2=80=9DOK sure, employ=
ees said, but how is it in Twitter=E2=80=99s best interest to go private?=
=E2=80=9CThis is the answer you don=E2=80=99t want to hear, right?=E2=80=9D=
 Agrawal said. =E2=80=9CTwitter is a public company owned by shareholders. =
There are other companies which may have other legal mechanics =E2=80=A6 Tw=
itter is not one of those companies.=E2=80=9DYou could imagine him giving a=
n answer that employees=C2=A0did=C2=A0want to hear. =E2=80=9CThis will make=
 our product stronger than ever.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CThis will give us the fu=
nding we need to improve the service.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CThis means we can f=
ocus on delighting our users rather than on the stock price.=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=9CThis means more free speech, which is a core value of ours.=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=9CElon Musk is a business visionary and he will run the company bett=
er.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CElon Musk loves Twitter and uses it way, way more tha=
n any of the current executives or directors, so he will run it better than=
 we do.=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t know. I=E2=80=99m not saying that I necess=
arily believe any of those things, or that Agrawal does, or that you should=
. I=E2=80=99m just saying you could imagine the CEO of a company, who had j=
ust voted to sell that company, telling the employees of the company that t=
hat was the right decision=C2=A0for the company, whatever that means. You c=
ould imagine some enthusiasm. You could imagine the CEO thinking that the p=
erson who values the company the most and will pay the most for it =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0Musk =E2=80=94=C2=A0will do good things with it.=C2=A0Agrawal said=
 the opposite. The implication is that Twitter has interests=C2=A0as a comp=
any=C2=A0that are distinct from=C2=A0the interests=C2=A0of its shareholders=
, but that Twitter=E2=80=99s board felt it had no choice but to do what was=
 best for shareholders even if it was worse for the company.=C2=A0This is a=
 traditional story, but it sounds a bit strange in 2022. Ten years ago if y=
ou had said that the job of a board of directors was to maximize the stock =
price, a lot of people would say =E2=80=9Cwell sure yes of course,=E2=80=9D=
 but now we have=C2=A0stakeholder capitalism=C2=A0and environmental, social=
 and governance investing. In 2019, the chief executive officers of many of=
 America=E2=80=99s biggest public companies (not Twitter) signed a Business=
 Roundtable statement that =E2=80=9Credefines the purpose of a corporation,=
=E2=80=9D saying that they =E2=80=9Cshare a fundamental commitment to all o=
f our stakeholders,=E2=80=9D not just shareholders. (I made fun of it here.=
)=C2=A0And the shareholders agree! In particular, Larry Fink at BlackRock I=
nc. has told CEOs that they =E2=80=9Cmust benefit all of their stakeholders=
, including shareholders, employees, customers, and the communities in whic=
h they operate=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9Cputting your company=E2=80=99s pu=
rpose at the foundation of your relationships with your stakeholders is cri=
tical to long-term success.=E2=80=9D (I made fun of this here and  here.) B=
ig companies now face activism whose message is not so much =E2=80=9Cmake c=
hanges to maximize the share price=E2=80=9D as it is =E2=80=9Cmake changes =
to improve your environmental and social impact=E2=80=9D; Exxon Mobil Corp.=
  lost a proxy fight=C2=A0to a tiny activist that wanted it to speed up its=
 transition away from fossil fuels.Now, to be clear, all of these trends ca=
n be described in terms of shareholder value. Being nice to stakeholders an=
d having a purpose and being environmentally friendly and so forth are all =
things that probably improve the long-term sustainability and profitability=
=C2=A0of a company, and shareholders can prefer them for purely financial r=
easons. Still they seem to have some independent weight in modern corporate=
 thought. The Business Roundtable CEOs want to weigh the interests of all s=
takeholders and sometimes=C2=A0prefer=C2=A0other stakeholders over sharehol=
ders; at least some ESG investors are surely willing to sacrifice financial=
 performance for environmental performance.And then Twitter=E2=80=99s CEO s=
hrugs and says, in effect, =E2=80=9Cmeh look this deal might be bad for our=
 users and employees and product and mission, but we can=E2=80=99t think ab=
out that; the price is right and my only duty is to shareholders.=E2=80=9D =
It=E2=80=99s strange!One thing to say about this story is that, as a descri=
ption of the board=E2=80=99s legal duties, it is debatable.[2] The foundati=
onal Delaware hostile-takeover cases=C2=A0from the 1980s explicitly say tha=
t a board can consider=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe impact on =E2=80=98constituencies=
=E2=80=99 other than shareholders (i.e., creditors, customers, employees, a=
nd perhaps even the community generally),=E2=80=9D[3] or =E2=80=9Cthe prese=
rvation of [a media company=E2=80=99s] =E2=80=98culture=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D a=
nd =E2=80=9Ceditorial integrity,=E2=80=9D[4] in rejecting a takeover offer;=
 shareholder value is not the only valid consideration. More recent cases f=
ocus more purely on shareholder value maximization, finding that =E2=80=9Cp=
romoting, protecting, or pursuing non-stockholder considerations must lead =
at some point to value for stockholder,=E2=80=9D and that a court =E2=80=9C=
cannot accept as valid =E2=80=A6 a corporate policy that specifically, clea=
rly, and admittedly seeks not to maximize the economic value of a for-profi=
t Delaware corporation for the benefit of its stockholders.=E2=80=9D[5]So i=
f Twitter=E2=80=99s board had said =E2=80=9CTwitter is not worth $54.20 per=
 share and never will be, but we declined Musk=E2=80=99s offer anyway becau=
se we think it is bad for users and the product,=E2=80=9D that would have b=
een at least a=C2=A0risky=C2=A0move. But if it had said =E2=80=9Cwe decline=
d Musk=E2=80=99s offer because we think it is bad for users and the product=
, and we think that if we continue to improve the product and user experien=
ce then in the long run this obviously important social network should be w=
orth more than $54.20 per share,=E2=80=9D that would have been a defensible=
 position even if, like, three-year earnings projections did not really sup=
port a $54.20 price.It would help, in making that case, if Twitter=E2=80=99=
s board and managers=C2=A0had a long-term plan. What is strange here is tha=
t the richest person on earth came in out of the blue with a not-particular=
ly-preemptive offer to buy a service that he is obsessed with and that seem=
s crucial to his success. Hearing that, you might think things like =E2=80=
=9Chuh this product must be pretty valuable.=E2=80=9D You might sit down an=
d try to think of ways to extract value from it, other than selling it to M=
usk at the first price he proposed. Twitter=E2=80=99s board had no ideas.Me=
anwhile you know who does? Elon Musk. Maybe? He seems to think that=C2=A0he=
 can make Twitter worth more than $54.20 per share: He has publicly denied =
wanting to make money from this deal, but he has  pitched his banks on how =
he will improve Twitter=E2=80=99s economics. Perhaps he is wrong, but he ha=
s a decent track record. And he just got here! He started buying Twitter st=
ock this year, and declined to do any nonpublic due diligence. Some random =
interloper has a plan to make Twitter worth more than $54.20, and has bet $=
33 billion of his own money that it will work. Meanwhile Twitter was tradin=
g in the $60s in October and Twitter=E2=80=99s board cannot fathom ever get=
ting it back to those levels. Their position is pretty much =E2=80=9Cwell w=
e destroyed some value for shareholders and we=E2=80=99re gonna go now, bye=
.=E2=80=9DBut it is worse than that. A lot of people think of Twitter as a =
public utility, a public trust, =E2=80=9Cthe town square,=E2=80=9D a compan=
y with an important social mission that many of its users and employees=C2=
=A0and Elon Musk=C2=A0care about deeply. And its CEO and board of directors=
 essentially can=E2=80=99t bring themselves to talk about it. When employee=
s asked him about what was best for the company, Agrawal could talk only ab=
out the shareholders. Elon Musk is not at all embarrassed to say that Twitt=
er has an important public mission, which is why he=E2=80=99s buying it. Bu=
t its current management can=E2=80=99t say that, which is why they=E2=80=99=
re selling it.I want to be clear here that I am=C2=A0not=C2=A0saying that i=
t was a bad decision, for Twitter=E2=80=99s product or users, to sell to El=
on Musk. I have no idea; that=E2=80=99s not the point. The point is that th=
e board seems to have put almost no weight on these questions. (Except Jack=
 Dorsey, who does seem to have thought that Musk would run Twitter better t=
han he did, and who seems happy about the sale.) I have  written this befor=
e, but the basic problem with Twitter=E2=80=99s management and board of dir=
ectors seems to be that they do not care about Twitter, as a company or as =
a product, so they are left to care about shareholders.[6] This seems bad f=
or everyone, including shareholders.There are a lot of tech companies whose=
 CEOs do not think this way.[7] They are not all companies with =E2=80=9Cot=
her legal mechanics,=E2=80=9D as Agrawal said: Tesla Inc. and Amazon.com In=
c. do not have dual-class stocks, and Elon Musk and Jeff Bezos have exactly=
 the same duties to their shareholders as Agrawal has to his. But what Tesl=
a and Amazon have are executives and boards who believe in what they are do=
ing, and shareholders who trust them to=C2=A0pursue a long-term vision.[8] =
If you ask Elon Musk about his decision-making, he would never say =E2=80=
=9CTesla is a public company owned by shareholders and I just try to maximi=
ze their profits.=E2=80=9D He would talk about his master plan to decarboni=
ze the world, he would talk about self-driving cars and rockets and tunnels=
. He cares about the product, not the shareholders. That=E2=80=99s why Musk=
=E2=80=99s shareholders are rich, and why Bezos=E2=80=99s are, and why Twit=
ter=E2=80=99s are selling at $54.20.
