By the time Elon Musk signed his deal to buy Twitter he was operating at qu=
ite a high level. He negotiated a gigantic leveraged buyout, and a gigantic=
 and unusual financing package for it, in near-record time and on terms ver=
y favorable to himself. But when he=C2=A0started=C2=A0his efforts to buy Tw=
itter, not all that long ago, it was all pretty ramshackle. He bought a bun=
ch of stock in the open market, and once he got above 5% of the stock he wa=
s required to disclose his position publicly on a Securities and Exchange C=
ommission filing. Due to some combination of sloppiness and disliking the S=
EC, he  filed the wrong form and filed it late.Ah well! The consequences of=
 this are probably a small fine, which is going to be annoying for everyone=
: He will be completely undeterred and unpunished, and he=E2=80=99ll get to=
 continue complaining=C2=A0that the SEC is harassing=C2=A0him.=C2=A0When th=
is all happened,  I wrote: =E2=80=9CDo you think he bothered to file an HSR=
 notification before buying the stock?=E2=80=9D The point here is:=09With s=
ome exceptions, if you are going to buy more than  $101 million worth of a =
company=E2=80=99s stock, you have to  file a notification with the Federal =
Trade Commission (under the Hart-Scott-Rodino Antitrust Improvements Act of=
 1976) and wait for FTC clearance before buying.=09Elon Musk was not exactl=
y careful about filling out all the forms before buying Twitter stock.And s=
ure enough!Elon Musk=E2=80=99s $44 billion Twitter takeover is unlikely to =
raise antitrust concerns. But what is already being scrutinized is Musk=E2=
=80=99s failure to comply with rules regarding disclosure of his initial 9%=
 stake, according to people with knowledge of the situation.The Federal Tra=
de Commission recently opened an inquiry into whether Musk failed to comply=
 with an antitrust reporting requirement as he amassed his initial 9.1% sta=
ke in Twitter between the end of January and the beginning of April, The In=
formation has learned. At the heart of the inquiry is whether Musk was init=
ially buying as someone who wanted to influence Twitter management or wheth=
er he saw himself as more of a passive shareholder. Notably, Musk=E2=80=99s=
 initial filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission categorized his=
 purchase as a passive stake=E2=80=94which immediately raised questions giv=
en his public comments about how Twitter is run.Here again the consequences=
 are probably a small fine, if that; the FTC seems slightly embarrassed=C2=
=A0that these antitrust rules apply to activist investments in public stock=
s, and it has proposed to change that. Still it is nice to know that Musk w=
as filling out=C2=A0all=C2=A0the forms wrong, not just the SEC=E2=80=99s.El=
sewhere in Twitter miscellany:=09There is a view out there that Musk=E2=80=
=99s deal is not really an agreement to buy Twitter, but is rather an optio=
n=C2=A0to buy Twitter: If he decides he doesn=E2=80=99t want to do it, he c=
an walk away and pay a $1 billion breakup fee. (See, e.g.,  Scott Galloway,=
  William Cohan,=C2=A0Fortune, the  Financial Times, etc.) This strikes me =
as a strange view in part because, you know, why would he walk away? The si=
mplest interpretation of why he spent so much of his own money and many hou=
rs in negotiations with banks and Twitter is that he really wants to buy Tw=
itter; if not, why go to all this trouble? Also, though, this view is wrong=
 as a contractual matter. As I   wrote last week: =E2=80=9CIf Musk changes =
his mind without a good reason, Twitter can force him to close the deal, as=
 long as his debt financing is available. That is, if all of the conditions=
 to closing are satisfied, and if Musk=E2=80=99s banks are willing to fund =
=E2=80=A6 then Twitter can force Musk to put up the $21 billion of cash tha=
t he has promised and close the deal.=E2=80=9D That is tricky =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0if Musk wants to back out then the financing might fall through on its o=
wn =E2=80=94=C2=A0and if it doesn=E2=80=99t work the damages are limited to=
 $1 billion. But he can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0just=C2=A0say =E2=80=9Cnever mind, h=
ere=E2=80=99s $1 billion.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=09=E2=80=9CTwitter is  rushing to =
reassure advertisers that it will remain a safe place for brands after Elon=
 Musk takes over the company,=E2=80=9D which is kind of a weird thing for T=
witter to say! How do they know what Elon Musk will do?=09Musk   sold about=
 $8.5 billion of Tesla Inc. stock last week to help pay for Twitter, which =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0seems =E2=80=A6=C2=A0early? The deal won=E2=80=99t close for=
 months. I suppose it does make sense to de-risk things a bit; of the $46-i=
sh billion that Musk will pay for Twitter, some $30-ish=C2=A0billion will c=
ome from his Tesla stock (either selling it for cash or putting it up as co=
llateral for margin loans). Waiting until closing to turn that stock into c=
ash increases the risk that he won=E2=80=99t be able to.
