At the Wall Street Journal, Richard Rubin writes about conservation easemen=
ts:Oglethorpe County, atop a pile of granite, has long been home to rock qu=
arries. Elberton, Ga., the self-proclaimed Granite Capital of the World, tu=
rns the region=E2=80=99s smooth, gray granite into cemetery headstones and =
statues.So promoters canvass Oglethorpe County for property that could beco=
me a quarry=E2=80=94and then recruit high-income investors who claim big ta=
x deductions for promising not to build a quarry. ...By extrapolating from =
claimed per-acre values in two public court cases from the county, there co=
uld be more than $500 million in federal tax deductions generated from a pl=
ace where all individuals=E2=80=99 adjusted gross income in 2019 was $314 m=
illion and charitable-donation deductions totaled $4.7 million.There is sor=
t of a nice economic trick here, which is that if you dig up all of the gra=
nite in Georgia and sell it for headstones, the price of granite will proba=
bly fall, while if you dig up=C2=A0none=C2=A0of it the price of granite wil=
l probably rise. The latter doesn=E2=80=99t help you much, if you are in th=
e business of digging up granite: If the price goes up but you have not dug=
 up any granite, you can=E2=80=99t make money selling it. But if you are in=
 the business of=C2=A0claiming tax deductions for not digging up granite, t=
hen the higher the price of granite is, the more money you can make by not =
digging it up.=C2=A0
