ther extraordinary transactions where heightened standards of judicial revi=
ew are applicable. In addition,=C2=A0Revlon=E2=80=99s emphasis on maximizin=
g short-term shareholder value has served as a convenient touchstone for ad=
vocates of shareholder primacy and has accordingly been used as a talking p=
oint to shape assumptions about fiduciary duties even outside the sale-of-c=
ontrol context, a result that was not intended. Around the same time that=
=C2=A0Revlon=C2=A0was decided, the Delaware Supreme Court also decided the=
=C2=A0Unocal=C2=A0and=C2=A0Household=C2=A0cases, which affirmed the board=
=E2=80=99s ability to consider all stakeholders in using a poison pill to d=
efend against a takeover=E2=80=94clearly confining=C2=A0Revlon=C2=A0to sale=
-of-control situations. The fiduciary duty of the board is to promote the v=
alue of the corporation. In fulfilling that duty, directors must exercise t=
heir business judgment in considering and reconciling the interests of vari=
ous stakeholders=E2=80=94including shareholders, employees, customers, supp=
liers, the environment and communities=E2=80=94and the attendant risks and =
opportunities for the corporation.=E2=80=9D[3] Unocal Corp. v. Mesa Petrole=
um Co., from 1985, which established the modern standard for evaluating tak=
eover defenses: =E2=80=9CIf a defensive measure is to come within the ambit=
