reat posed. This entails an analysis by the directors of the nature of the =
takeover bid and its effect on the corporate enterprise. Examples of such c=
oncerns may include: inadequacy of the price offered, nature and timing of =
the offer, questions of illegality, the impact on =E2=80=98constituencies=
=E2=80=99 other than shareholders (i.e., creditors, customers, employees, a=
nd perhaps even the community generally), the risk of nonconsummation, and =
the quality of securities being offered in the exchange.=E2=80=9D[4]=C2=A0P=
aramount Communications Inc. v. Time Inc., from 1989, allowing Time=E2=80=
=99s board to decline a higher-priced cash takeover offer to pursue a merge=
r that better preserved its editorial independence: =E2=80=9CDelaware law i=
mposes on a board of directors the duty to manage the business and affairs =
of the corporation. =E2=80=A6 This broad mandate includes a conferred autho=
rity to set a corporate course of action, including time frame, designed to=
 enhance corporate profitability. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Absent a limited set of ci=
rcumstances as defined under Revlon, a board of directors, while always req=
uired to act in an informed manner, is not under any per se duty to maximiz=
e shareholder value in the short term, even in the context of a takeover. =
=E2=80=A6 The record attests to the zealousness of Time's executives, fully=
 supported by their directors, in seeing to the preservation of Time's =E2=
=80=98culture,=E2=80=99 i.e., its perceived editorial integrity in journali=
sm. We find ample evidence in the record to support the Chancellor's conclu=
sion that the Time board's decision to expand the business of the company t=
hrough its March 3 merger with Warner was entitled to the protection of the=
 business judgment rule.=E2=80=9D[5] EBay Domestic Holdings Inc. v. Newmark=
, from 2010: =E2=80=9CPromoting, protecting, or pursuing non-stockholder co=
nsiderations must lead at some point to value for stockholders. When direct=
or decisions are reviewed under the business judgment rule, this Court will=
 not question rational judgments about how promoting non-stockholder intere=
sts=E2=80=94be it through making a charitable contribution, paying employee=
s higher salaries and benefits, or more general norms like promoting a part=
icular corporate culture=E2=80=94ultimately promote stockholder value. Unde=
r the Unocal standard, however, the directors must act within the range of =
reasonableness. =E2=80=A6 Having chosen a for-profit corporate form, the cr=
aigslist directors are bound by the fiduciary duties and standards that acc=
ompany that form. Those standards include acting to promote the value of th=
e corporation for the benefit of its stockholders. The =E2=80=98Inc.=E2=80=
=99 after the company name has to mean at least that. Thus, I cannot accept=
 as valid for the purposes of implementing the Rights Plan a corporate poli=
cy that specifically, clearly, and admittedly seeks not to maximize the eco=
nomic value of a for-profit Delaware corporation for the benefit of its sto=
ckholders=E2=80=94no matter whether those stockholders are individuals of m=
odest means or a corporate titan of online commerce.=E2=80=9D[6] One half-b=
aked theory of mine is that the fact that Twitter=E2=80=99s directors own s=
o little stock makes them especially focused on short-term shareholder valu=
e. If you are a director of a public company and you own 5% of its stock, t=
hen (1) you believe in the company (that=E2=80=99s why you bought all that =
stock) and (2) you can head off criticism by saying that you have skin in t=
he game. If you own only a tiny slice of the stock, then (1) you probably d=
on=E2=80=99t care all that much about the company=E2=80=99s social mission =
and (2) you are very self-conscious about having no skin in the game, so yo=
u end up deferring to other shareholders.[7] Famously Mark Zuckerberg, who =
wrote, when Facebook Inc. went public in 2012, that =E2=80=9CFacebook was n=
ot originally founded to be a company. We=E2=80=99ve always cared primarily=
 about our social mission, the services we=E2=80=99re building and the peop=
le who use them. This is a different approach for a public company to take.=
 =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Simply put: we don=E2=80=99t build services to make money; =
we make money to build better services.=E2=80=9D Since then Facebook has ha=
d let=E2=80=99s say a mixed social impact and made a gazillion dollars, pre=
sumably because Zuckerberg cares about his social mission and not making mo=
ney.[8] Also executives who own a lot of stock, to be fair, though that cut=
s both ways; see footnote 6.
