</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can tell a simple story about Elon=
 Musk=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27=
570320.267604/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwM=
jItMDQtMjYvZWxvbi1nb3QtaGlzLWRlYWw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwMjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRt=
X21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNTAyJnV0bV9=
jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB074fe894" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> pendi=
ng acquisition of Twitter Inc.</a> that goes like this. Musk offered Twitte=
r $54.20 per share in cash. Twitter=E2=80=99s board of directors consulted =
some bankers, who told them that the market price of Twitter=E2=80=99s stoc=
k was lower than $54.20, and that it would likely stay lower in the near fu=
ture, due to Twitter not making all that much money. The board of directors=
 had a fiduciary duty to maximize the stock price for those shareholders. T=
hey looked for higher bids than $54.20, but none materialized. So they had =
no choice but to take Musk=E2=80=99s $54.20.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">This simple story is the one that, for instance, Twitter Chief Executive =
Officer Parag Agrawal told Twitter employees last week.[1]=C2=A0<a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27570320.267604/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cucGxhdGZvcm1lci5uZXdzL3AvaW5zaWRlLXR3aXR0ZXJzLWVtb3Rpb25hbC1mcmlkYXk/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb1aa019c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Casey Newton reports</a>=C2=A0on a T=
witter all-hands call Friday:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">W=
hy did Agrawal vote in favor of the deal? He spoke in the bloodless languag=
e of, well, a fiduciary.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Agrawal:=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9CAs I=E2=80=99ve said, the board decides based on two factors. We act =
in the interest of our shareholders and look for value for them in the long=
 term. Our job is to think about the price, and consider any offer on the t=
able. And we compare that against the intrinsic value of the company based =
on the future-looking outlooks we have financially.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe get a lot of advice from several lawyers and =
bankers in the process =E2=80=A6 And when we looked at all the information =
and all of the data, every one of us concluded that based on our fiduciary =
responsibility =E2=80=A6 this offer at the price it ended up at was in the =
best long-term interest of our shareholders.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">OK sure, employees said, but how is it in Twitter=E2=80=99s best=
 interest to go private?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis is t=
he answer you don=E2=80=99t want to hear, right?=E2=80=9D Agrawal said. =E2=
=80=9CTwitter is a public company owned by shareholders. There are other co=
mpanies which may have other legal mechanics =E2=80=A6 Twitter is not one o=
f those companies.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yo=
u could imagine him giving an answer that employees=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>=
want to hear. =E2=80=9CThis will make our product stronger than ever.=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=9CThis will give us the funding we need to improve the service.=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CThis means we can focus on delighting our users rather t=
han on the stock price.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CThis means more free speech, whic=
h is a core value of ours.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CElon Musk is a business vision=
ary and he will run the company better.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CElon Musk loves T=
witter and uses it way, way more than any of the current executives or dire=
ctors, so he will run it better than we do.=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t know. =
I=E2=80=99m not saying that I necessarily believe any of those things, or t=
hat Agrawal does, or that you should. I=E2=80=99m just saying you could ima=
gine the CEO of a company, who had just voted to sell that company, telling=
 the employees of the company that that was the right decision=C2=A0<em>for=
 the company</em>, whatever that means. You could imagine some enthusiasm. =
You could imagine the CEO thinking that the person who values the company t=
he most and will pay the most for it =E2=80=94=C2=A0Musk =E2=80=94=C2=A0wil=
l do good things with it.=C2=A0Agrawal said the opposite. The implication i=
s that Twitter has interests=C2=A0<em>as a company</em>=C2=A0that are disti=
nct from=C2=A0the interests=C2=A0<em>of its shareholders</em>, but that Twi=
tter=E2=80=99s board felt it had no choice but to do what was best for shar=
eholders even if it was worse for the company.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">This is a traditional story, but it sounds a bit strange in 2022.=
 Ten years ago if you had said that the job of a board of directors was to =
maximize the stock price, a lot of people would say =E2=80=9Cwell sure yes =
of course,=E2=80=9D but now we have=C2=A0stakeholder capitalism=C2=A0and en=
vironmental, social and governance investing. In 2019, the chief executive =
officers of many of America=E2=80=99s biggest public companies (<a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27570320.267604/aHR0cHM6Ly9vc=
