"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">wil=
ling to sacrifice financial performance</a> for environmental performance.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then Twitter=E2=80=99s CEO shrugs and s=
ays, in effect, =E2=80=9Cmeh look this deal might be bad for our users and =
employees and product and mission, but we can=E2=80=99t think about that; t=
he price is right and my only duty is to shareholders.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99=
s strange!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing to say about this stor=
y is that, as a description of the board=E2=80=99s legal duties, it is deba=
table.[2] The foundational Delaware hostile-takeover cases=C2=A0from the 19=
80s explicitly say that a board can consider=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe impact on =
=E2=80=98constituencies=E2=80=99 other than shareholders (i.e., creditors, =
customers, employees, and perhaps even the community generally),=E2=80=9D[3=
] or =E2=80=9Cthe preservation of [a media company=E2=80=99s] =E2=80=98cult=
ure=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ceditorial integrity,=E2=80=9D[4] in reje=
cting a takeover offer; shareholder value is not the only valid considerati=
on. More recent cases focus more purely on shareholder value maximization, =
finding that =E2=80=9Cpromoting, protecting, or pursuing non-stockholder co=
nsiderations must lead at some point to value for stockholder,=E2=80=9D and=
 that a court =E2=80=9Ccannot accept as valid =E2=80=A6 a corporate policy =
that specifically, clearly, and admittedly seeks not to maximize the econom=
ic value of a for-profit Delaware corporation for the benefit of its stockh=
olders.=E2=80=9D[5]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So if Twitter=E2=80=99s=
 board had said =E2=80=9CTwitter is not worth $54.20 per share and never wi=
ll be, but we declined Musk=E2=80=99s offer anyway because we think it is b=
ad for users and the product,=E2=80=9D that would have been at least a=C2=
=A0<em>risky=C2=A0</em>move. But if it had said =E2=80=9Cwe declined Musk=
=E2=80=99s offer because we think it is bad for users and the product, and =
we think that if we continue to improve the product and user experience the=
n in the long run this obviously important social network should be worth m=
ore than $54.20 per share,=E2=80=9D that would have been a defensible posit=
ion even if, like, three-year earnings projections did not really support a=
 $54.20 price.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It would help, in making tha=
t case, if Twitter=E2=80=99s board and managers=C2=A0<em>had a long-term pl=
an</em>. What is strange here is that the richest person on earth came in o=
ut of the blue with a not-particularly-preemptive offer to buy a service th=
at he is obsessed with and that seems <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/27570320.267604/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucmVhZG1hcmdpbnMuY29tL3A=
vZWxvbnMtZ2lhbnQtcGFja2FnZT9zPXI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB12567f35" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>crucial to his success</a>. Hearing that, you might think things like =E2=
=80=9Chuh this product must be pretty valuable.=E2=80=9D You might sit down=
 and try to think of ways to extract value from it, other than selling it t=
o Musk at the first price he proposed. Twitter=E2=80=99s board had no ideas=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile you know who does? Elon Musk. M=
aybe? He seems to think that=C2=A0he can make Twitter worth more than $54.2=
0 per share: He has publicly denied wanting to make money from this deal, b=
ut he has <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27570320=
.267604/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMjg=
vbXVzay1zLXR3aXR0ZXItcGl0Y2gtZmVhdHVyZWQtam9iLWN1dHMtb3RoZXItd2F5cy10by1tYW=
tlLW1vbmV5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MDIyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX=
3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDUwMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVm=
Zg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe22428a8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> pitched his banks</a> on how=
 he will improve Twitter=E2=80=99s economics. Perhaps he is wrong, but he h=
as a decent track record. And he just got here! He started <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27570320.267604/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2=
VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzAwMDE0MTgwOTEvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIyMDQyODYzL=
3RtMjIxMTc1N2QxX3NjMTNkLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB04ff63f8" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
buying Twitter stock</a> this year, and declined to do any nonpublic due di=
ligence. Some random interloper has a plan to make Twitter worth more than =
$54.20, and has bet $33 billion of his own money that it will work. Meanwhi=
le Twitter was trading in the $60s in October and Twitter=E2=80=99s board c=
annot fathom ever getting it back to those levels. Their position is pretty=
 much =E2=80=9Cwell we destroyed some value for shareholders and we=E2=80=
=99re gonna go now, bye.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it is=
 worse than that. A lot of people think of Twitter as a public utility, a p=
ublic trust, =E2=80=9Cthe town square,=E2=80=9D a company with an important=
 social mission that many of its users and employees=C2=A0<em>and Elon Musk=
=C2=A0</em>care about deeply. And its CEO and board of directors essentiall=
y can=E2=80=99t bring themselves to talk about it. When employees asked him=
 about what was best for the company, Agrawal could talk only about the sha=
reholders. Elon Musk is not at all embarrassed to say that Twitter has an i=
mportant public mission, which is why he=E2=80=99s buying it. But its curre=
nt management can=E2=80=99t say that, which is why they=E2=80=99re selling =
it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I want to be clear here that I am=C2=A0=
<em>not=C2=A0</em>saying that it was a bad decision, for Twitter=E2=80=99s =
product or users, to sell to Elon Musk. I have no idea; that=E2=80=99s not =
the point. The point is that the board seems to have put almost no weight o=
n these questions. (Except <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/27570320.267604/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy90aGUtc2hhZG=
93LWNyZXctd2hvLWVuY291cmFnZWQtZWxvbi1tdXNrcy10d2l0dGVyLXRha2VvdmVyLXRlc2xhL=
WphY2stZG9yc2V5LTExNjUxMjYwMTE5/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB48a8c597" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
Jack Dorsey</a>, who does seem to have thought that Musk would run Twitter =
better than he did, and who seems happy about the sale.) I have <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27570320.267604/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMjUvZWxvbi1jbG9zZXMt=
aW4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwMjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmN=
lPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNTAyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB6a2022b8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> written this before</a>, but the bas=
ic problem with Twitter=E2=80=99s management and board of directors seems t=
o be that they do not care about Twitter, as a company or as a product, so =
they are left to care about shareholders.[6] This seems bad for everyone, i=
ncluding shareholders.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are a lot of t=
ech companies whose CEOs do not think this way.[7] They are not all compani=
es with =E2=80=9Cother legal mechanics,=E2=80=9D as Agrawal said: Tesla Inc=
. and Amazon.com Inc. do not have dual-class stocks, and Elon Musk and Jeff=
 Bezos have exactly the same duties to their shareholders as Agrawal has to=
 his. But what Tesla and Amazon have are executives and boards who believe =
in what they are doing, and shareholders who trust them to=C2=A0pursue a lo=
ng-term vision.[8] If you ask Elon Musk about his decision-making, he would=
 never say =E2=80=9CTesla is a public company owned by shareholders and I j=
ust try to maximize their profits.=E2=80=9D He would talk about his master =
plan to decarbonize the world, he would talk about self-driving cars and ro=
ckets and tunnels. He cares about the product, not the shareholders. That=
=E2=80=99s why Musk=E2=80=99s shareholders are rich, and why Bezos=E2=80=99=
s are, and why Twitter=E2=80=99s are selling at $54.20.</p><table class=3D"=
