nty, atop a pile of granite, has long been home to rock quarries. Elberton,=
 Ga., the self-proclaimed Granite Capital of the World, turns the region=E2=
=80=99s smooth, gray granite into cemetery headstones and statues.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So promoters canvass Oglethorpe County for property=
 that could become a quarry=E2=80=94and then recruit high-income investors =
who claim big tax deductions for promising not to build a quarry. ...</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By extrapolating from claimed per-acre values in=
 two public court cases from the county, there could be more than $500 mill=
ion in federal tax deductions generated from a place where all individuals=
=E2=80=99 adjusted gross income in 2019 was $314 million and charitable-don=
ation deductions totaled $4.7 million.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">There is sort of a nice economic trick here, which is that if you =
dig up all of the granite in Georgia and sell it for headstones, the price =
of granite will probably fall, while if you dig up=C2=A0<em>none=C2=A0</em>=
of it the price of granite will probably rise. The latter doesn=E2=80=99t h=
elp you much, if you are in the business of digging up granite: If the pric=
e goes up but you have not dug up any granite, you can=E2=80=99t make money=
 selling it. But if you are in the business of=C2=A0<em>claiming tax deduct=
ions for not digging up granite</em>, then the higher the price of granite =
is, the more money you can make by not digging it up.=C2=A0</p><table class=
