eekend <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27570320.26=
7604/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMi8wNC8zMC90ZWNobm9sb2d5L3R3aXR0ZX=
ItYm9hcmQtZWxvbi1tdXNrLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf1da0c62" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
the New York Times reported</a> on the board=E2=80=99s decision-making, and=
, again, the price seems to have been=C2=A0the main consideration: =E2=80=
=9CAt Twitter, [Chairman Bret]=C2=A0Taylor weighed employee uncertainty and=
 the societal implications of a deal versus the board=E2=80=99s fiduciary d=
uty, people with knowledge of the situation said. That meant making a decis=
ion based on whether Twitter could reasonably achieve a value better than w=
hat Mr. Musk had put forward.=E2=80=9D And Taylor told employees: =E2=80=9C=
What I=E2=80=99ll tell you is that based on the analysis and the perception=
 of risk, certainty and value, the board unanimously decided the offer from=
 Elon represented the best value for our shareholders.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Outsid=
e commentators also embraced this view. For instance,=C2=A0on April 14, whe=
n Musk first announced his offer, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/27570320.267604/aHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvdGhlLXR3aXR0ZXItYm9=
hcmRzLXBhbmljLXJvb20v/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe6516fc0" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">William Co=
han wrote</a>=C2=A0that =E2=80=9Cthe most important question=E2=80=9D for t=
he board was=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwhether the $54.20 price is =E2=80=98fair,=E2=80=
=99 from a financial point of view,=E2=80=9D for shareholders, and that =E2=
=80=9CIf the answer is yes=E2=80=94and I believe it is, or soon will be=E2=
=80=94then the board will have little choice but to accept Musk=E2=80=99s o=
ffer.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[2] A good su=
mmary is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27570320.=
267604/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lk=
PTI1NzYzODk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc7a45d5d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">this 2015 paper</a> =
by former Delaware Supreme Court Chief Justice Leo Strine, who takes a stro=
ng view that in fact the sole fiduciary duty of a company=E2=80=99s board o=
f directors is to its shareholders, but who goes through the arguments on b=
oth sides. On the not-just-shareholders side, I like <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27570320.267604/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3JwZ292Lmxh=
dy5oYXJ2YXJkLmVkdS8yMDE5LzA4LzI0L3N0YWtlaG9sZGVyLWdvdmVybmFuY2UtYW5kLXRoZS1=
maWR1Y2lhcnktZHV0aWVzLW9mLWRpcmVjdG9ycy8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa835ea56"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">this 2019 memo</a> from Marty Lipton et al.: =E2=80=9CTo be clear,=
 Delaware law does not enshrine a principle of shareholder primacy or precl=
ude a board of directors from considering the interests of other stakeholde=
rs. Nor does the law of any other state. Although much attention has been g=
iven to the=C2=A0Revlon=C2=A0doctrine, which suggests that the board must a=
ttempt to achieve the highest value reasonably available to shareholders, t=
hat doctrine is narrowly limited to situations where the board has determin=
ed to sell control of the company and either all or a preponderant percenta=
ge of the consideration being paid is cash or the transaction will result i=
n a controlling shareholder. Indeed, the=C2=A0Revlon=C2=A0doctrine has play=
ed an outsized role in fiduciary duty jurisprudence not because it articula=
tes the ultimate nature and objective of the board=E2=80=99s fiduciary duty=
, but rather because most fiduciary duty litigation arises in the context o=
f mergers or other extraordinary transactions where heightened standards of=
 judicial review are applicable. In addition,=C2=A0Revlon=E2=80=99s emphasi=
s on maximizing short-term shareholder value has served as a convenient tou=
chstone for advocates of shareholder primacy and has accordingly been used =
as a talking point to shape assumptions about fiduciary duties even outside=
 the sale-of-control context, a result that was not intended. Around the sa=
me time that=C2=A0Revlon=C2=A0was decided, the Delaware Supreme Court also =
decided the=C2=A0Unocal=C2=A0and=C2=A0Household=C2=A0cases, which affirmed =
the board=E2=80=99s ability to consider all stakeholders in using a poison =
pill to defend against a takeover=E2=80=94clearly confining=C2=A0Revlon=C2=
=A0to sale-of-control situations. The fiduciary duty of the board is to pro=
mote the value of the corporation. In fulfilling that duty, directors must =
exercise their business judgment in considering and reconciling the interes=
ts of various stakeholders=E2=80=94including shareholders, employees, custo=
mers, suppliers, the environment and communities=E2=80=94and the attendant =
risks and opportunities for the corporation.=E2=80=9D</em></p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;"><em>[3] <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/27570320.267604/aHR0cHM6Ly9sYXcuanVzdGlhLmNvbS9jYXNlcy9kZWxhd2FyZS9zd=
XByZW1lLWNvdXJ0LzE5ODUvNDkzLWEtMmQtOTQ2LTkuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
116c9ddc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">Unocal Corp. v. Mesa Petroleum Co.</a>, from 1985, which =
established the modern standard for evaluating takeover defenses: =E2=80=9C=
If a defensive measure is to come within the ambit of the business judgment=
 rule, it must be reasonable in relation to the threat posed. This entails =
an analysis by the directors of the nature of the takeover bid and its effe=
ct on the corporate enterprise. Examples of such concerns may include: inad=
equacy of the price offered, nature and timing of the offer, questions of i=
llegality, the impact on =E2=80=98constituencies=E2=80=99 other than shareh=
olders (i.e., creditors, customers, employees, and perhaps even the communi=
ty generally), the risk of nonconsummation, and the quality of securities b=
eing offered in the exchange.=E2=80=9D</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
><em>[4]=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2757=
0320.267604/aHR0cHM6Ly9sYXcuanVzdGlhLmNvbS9jYXNlcy9kZWxhd2FyZS9zdXByZW1lLWN=
vdXJ0LzE5OTAvNTcxLWEtMmQtMTE0MC01Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1f899f90"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">Paramount Communications Inc. v. Time Inc.</a>, from 1989, allowin=
g Time=E2=80=99s board to decline a higher-priced cash takeover offer to pu=
rsue a merger that better preserved its editorial independence: =E2=80=9CDe=
laware law imposes on a board of directors the duty to manage the business =
and affairs of the corporation. =E2=80=A6 This broad mandate includes a con=
ferred authority to set a corporate course of action, including time frame,=
 designed to enhance corporate profitability. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Absent a limit=
ed set of circumstances as defined under Revlon, a board of directors, whil=
e always required to act in an informed manner, is not under any per se dut=
y to maximize shareholder value in the short term, even in the context of a=
 takeover. =E2=80=A6 The record attests to the zealousness of Time's execut=
ives, fully supported by their directors, in seeing to the preservation of =
Time's =E2=80=98culture,=E2=80=99 i.e., its perceived editorial integrity i=
n journalism. We find ample evidence in the record to support the Chancello=
r's conclusion that the Time board's decision to expand the business of the=
 company through its March 3 merger with Warner was entitled to the protect=
ion of the business judgment rule.=E2=80=9D</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;"><em>[5] <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2757=
0320.267604/aHR0cHM6Ly9oMm8ubGF3LmhhcnZhcmQuZWR1L2Nhc2VzLzM0NzI/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBec9e0c0c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">EBay Domestic Holdings Inc. v. Newmark</a>,=
 from 2010: =E2=80=9CPromoting, protecting, or pursuing non-stockholder con=
siderations must lead at some point to value for stockholders. When directo=
r decisions are reviewed under the business judgment rule, this Court will =
not question rational judgments about how promoting non-stockholder interes=
ts=E2=80=94be it through making a charitable contribution, paying employees=
 higher salaries and benefits, or more general norms like promoting a parti=
cular corporate culture=E2=80=94ultimately promote stockholder value. Under=
 the Unocal standard, however, the directors must act within the range of r=
easonableness. =E2=80=A6 Having chosen a for-profit corporate form, the cra=
igslist directors are bound by the fiduciary duties and standards that acco=
mpany that form. Those standards include acting to promote the value of the=
 corporation for the benefit of its stockholders. The =E2=80=98Inc.=E2=80=
=99 after the company name has to mean at least that. Thus, I cannot accept=
 as valid for the purposes of implementing the Rights Plan a corporate poli=
cy that specifically, clearly, and admittedly seeks not to maximize the eco=
nomic value of a for-profit Delaware corporation for the benefit of its sto=
ckholders=E2=80=94no matter whether those stockholders are individuals of m=
odest means or a corporate titan of online commerce.=E2=80=9D</em></p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[6] One half-baked theory of mine is that the f=
act that Twitter=E2=80=99s directors own so little stock makes them especia=
lly focused on short-term shareholder value. If you are a director of a pub=
lic company and you own 5% of its stock, then (1) you believe in the compan=
y (that=E2=80=99s why you bought all that stock) and (2) you can head off c=
riticism by saying that you have skin in the game. If you own only a tiny s=
lice of the stock, then (1) you probably don=E2=80=99t care all that much a=
bout the company=E2=80=99s social mission and (2) you are very self-conscio=
us about having no skin in the game, so you end up deferring to other share=
holders.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[7] Famously Mark Zuckerb=
erg, who wrote, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27=
570320.267604/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEzMjY4M=
DEvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTEyMDM0NTE3L2QyODc5NTRkczEuaHRtI3RvYzI4Nzk1NF8xMA/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB84f4ea4c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">when Facebook Inc. went public in 2012</a=
>, that =E2=80=9CFacebook was not originally founded to be a company. We=E2=
=80=99ve always cared primarily about our social mission, the services we=
=E2=80=99re building and the people who use them. This is a different appro=
ach for a public company to take. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Simply put: we don=E2=80=
=99t build services to make money; we make money to build better services.=
=E2=80=9D Since then Facebook has had let=E2=80=99s say a mixed social impa=
ct and made a gazillion dollars, presumably because Zuckerberg cares about =
his social mission and not making money.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;"><em>[8] Also executives who own a lot of stock, to be fair, though that =
cuts both ways; see footnote 6.</em></p>
</td>
